BENIN  – The National Directorate of Employment (NDE) has commenced training of 20 unemployed persons in the Community Based Train­ing Scheme (CBTS) in Edo State. The scheme was meant to create and make a direct impact on the directorate within the rural areas of the state. Mallam Abubakar Fik­po, NDE Director General, who flagged off the cere­mony in Benin at the week­end, highlighted the main objectives of the CBTS. Wife Reportedly Stabs Husband’s Nephew Over Broken Mirror Analysing The Retaining, Removal Of Nigeria’s Oil Subsidy According to Fikpo, who was represented by the Edo State Coordinator of the NDE, Mr Solomon Edobor, the scheme would create skill persons in both the rural areas as well as semi urban areas. NDE, he said, had gra­ciously directed the voca­tional skills development to recruit 20 unemployed persons in the state who would be expected to un­dergo three months train­ing. He also said that the training would expose them to specialised skills training, demand driv­en emerging marketable skills such as cosmetology, barbing, fashion and hair­dressing. Fikpo asserted that the trainees upon completion of their training would be­come self-employed, create employment/wealth and thereby reduce poverty, just as he added that the programme would also re­duce the rural/urban mi­gration in the country. Responding, Head of the Local Government Administration and Act­ing Chairman of Egor Lo­cal Government Area, Mr O. OIgbinigie, thanked the NDE for selecting Egor Local Government Area as a base of the pro­gramme.